Package com.deliburd.extrataskschedulers

Class StealingCallbackExecutors

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.deliburd.extrataskschedulers.StealingCallbackExecutors
  • public final class StealingCallbackExecutors
extends Object
    A static utility class containing methods to get different StealingCallbackExecutors including fixed thread pools, cached thread pools, and single thread executors.

      • newFixedThreadPool

        public static StealingCallbackExecutor newFixedThreadPool​(int threadCount)
        Creates a StealingCallbackExecutor with a fixed amount of threads in its pool and with work stealing enabled by default. These threads do not expire and once created, last until the pool is shut down. This kind of thread pool is good for non-blocking tasks.
        Parameters:
        threadCount - The amount of threads that the fixed thread pool can have.
        Returns:
        The new fixed thread pool.
        See Also:
        StealingCallbackExecutor

      • newFixedThreadPool

        public static StealingCallbackExecutor newFixedThreadPool​(int threadCount,
                                                          RejectedExecutionHandler rejectedHandler)
        Creates a StealingCallbackExecutor with a fixed amount of threads in its pool and with work stealing enabled by default. These threads do not expire and once created, last until the pool is shut down. A RejectedExecutionHandler can be specified to handle rejected tasks. This kind of thread pool is good for non-blocking tasks.
        Parameters:
        threadCount - The amount of threads that the fixed thread pool can have.
        rejectedHandler - The handler to use for rejected tasks.
        Returns:
        The new fixed thread pool.
        See Also:
        StealingCallbackExecutor

      • newCachedThreadPool

        public static StealingCallbackExecutor newCachedThreadPool()
        Creates a StealingCallbackExecutor that expands the amount of threads it has dynamically so that each new task gets its own thread if none is available. Work stealing is disabled by default because a new thread or an idle thread is used to execute each new task, leaving, in general, no opportunity for work to be stolen. These threads expire after 60 seconds of inactivity. This kind of thread pool is good for low throughput, blocking task submission.
        Returns:
        The new cached thread pool.
        See Also:
        StealingCallbackExecutor

      • newSingleThreadExecutor

        public static StealingCallbackExecutor newSingleThreadExecutor()
        Creates a StealingCallbackExecutor that can only have 1 thread in it and with work stealing enabled. This thread will not expire until the pool is shut down.
        Returns:
        The new single threaded thread pool.
        See Also:
        StealingCallbackExecutor
